Encapsulation in a OO language means that fields declared private in one class may not be access from an instance method of another class, but can be accessed from within the instance methods of the defining class.

Discuss, what do you think?

Encapsulation in object-orientated languages has many benefits. For the user, it promotes their convenience as the code provides results but does not force knowing the details of the implementation onto the user. Good encapsulation also reduces dependency as they are not relying on fields other than their own. It can also increase security as the class's internal data cannot be accessed from the outside.

If the question is asking if the statement is true, we believe it is because private fields cannot be accessed from any other class except the defining one. Encapsulation controls the access of its data, so this statement is true.

Total[10]: 5
The statement is not true across all languages. For example, Ruby restrics private to instance and not class level
